You need a graphing calculator to solve quadratic equations and obtain their roots. Casio calculators are user-friendly, Texas calculators are not. Here, I will show how to get the roots first using a Casio calculator and then using a Texas calculator.
You need to follow the following steps to solve a quadratic formula in a Casio fx 9750GII:
\begin{solutionbox} \begin{enumerate}[label=\protect\circled{\color{white}\arabic*}]
\item \begin{bf}Step one:\end{bf}   Press Menu and 8.
 \item \begin{bf}Step two:\end{bf} Press the Poly (F2) menu.\ and select the degree: 2. Now enter the a, b, and c coefficients of the polynomial.
\item \begin{bf}Step three:\end{bf} At this point, you will have the two roots
\end{enumerate}
\end{solutionbox} 
You need to follow the following steps to solve a quadratic formula in a Texas TI 84:
\begin{solutionbox} \begin{enumerate}[label=\protect\circled{\color{white}\arabic*}]
\item \begin{bf}Step one:\end{bf} Select: PRGM key, select New, type QUAD using letter keys, press ENTER (this opens the new program) 
 \item \begin{bf}Step two:\end{bf} Select: PRGM, I/O, Prompt, press ENTER, type: ALPHA+A, then press the comma key, ALPHA+B and comma, ALPHA+C, press ENTER
 \item \begin{bf}Step three:\end{bf} Write the following equations using Alpha/Numeric keys: (-B+sqrt(B$^2$ -4AC))/(2A)STO X, press ENTER
\item \begin{bf}Step four:\end{bf} Write the following equations using Alpha/Numeric keys: (-B-sqrt(B$^2$ -4AC))/(2A) STO Y, press ENTER


\item \begin{bf}Step five:\end{bf} Select: PRGM, I/O, Disp, type: "ROOTS EQUAL" (with quotes), press comma, ALPHA+X press comma ALPHA+Y, press ENTER.

\item \begin{bf}Step six:\end{bf} Press 2nd MODE to QUIT program and save. 

\item \begin{bf}Step seven:\end{bf} Press PRGM key, select QUAD, press ENTER twice to start program. It will then ask for A=?, B=?, and C=? Enter values for A, B, and C pressing ENTER after each value it will then display the two roots if they are real.


\end{enumerate}
\end{solutionbox} 